caption: The food and service were beyond my expectations. We surely loved the ambience of this spot. Nice spot to take my family out for dinner.

Happy to report that Sunshine Seafood Restaurant has re-opened after renovation. At 27 Division Street is the best authentic Banquet style dim sum restaurant in Chinatown. This place succeeds without any p.r., press, advertising or crowd sourced nonsense.  None of the others compare, either in atmosphere, quality, cleanliness or service. The place is always bustling with Chinese families in celebration, the dim sum carts are plentiful, the varieties endless, the price points low. They are also a fine option at dinnertime, especially excellent are their Cantonese Classics including fresh seafood and shellfish options. It is always a joy and a comfort to come here.

Just opened and everything looks super fancy and clean. They recently changed the interior. I went here for dim sum and dinner with big family. They give big portions which is very nice. Would come back again considering how the service and food was great.

A good place for family style food.  The portions are good and quality is better than most Chinese places around the area.  The good thing is, it is never packed so no wait times on week days.  Weekend is a totally different.  The staff is friendly as well.  Overall good food for a good price.
Incredible food. Great service.
Food is delicious, just it.

I think the food is okay but the crowds for dim sum are huge on the weekends. Even at 11:30 am it's packed with a wait.  The tables are kind of dirty (they do use tablecloths but they may be a little soiled from previous people). They change them sometimes, as they did at our table while we were all eating.  You get seated most likely with about 2 or 3 other parties at your big round table, at least on a weekend. So this does get uncomfortable. You really have to be in the mood to talk to other people.  There is a huge language barrier with everyone here, and the cart ladies will put items on your table (for you) if you even look at it for 2 seconds. So BE PREPARED to say "NO" and WAVE "NO" . Soy sauce was hard to get from the cart ladies. But there are small things of chinese mustard and hot chili sauce on the tables for each party.  Cash only.  When paying, even cashier told us to leave a tip, which is pretty uncomfortable when that's all only word the are saying at you as you pay.  idk. Food OK. Service and feel of things, kind of uncomfortable. Maybe if I go here again, we will just order off the regular menu too.  But likely you will be at one of these big tables.  Very loud on weekend.  No one at the tables seemed to have water, so if I remember to, I will bring our own bottles of water.  Tea does come right out. Not sure if they charge for tea. I saw something for 80 cents.  It's kind of a mixed bag of experiences.

Good place for dim sum in Chinatown.  Busy when I arrived, most of the customers appear to be locals.  When it is busy, expect to share a table with strangers.  The carts came around slowly, but the staff also carried trays of hot dim sum around with trays.  The selection was tasty and the prices reasonable.
It's convenient because you can just point and choose, but you often have to guess what it is. Good luck trying to find a seat on the weekend.

I was looking for a non-touristy/cheap/good quality option for dim sum in Chinatown. My friend (who lives in Chinatown) suggested Sunshine and it was a great recommendation! I normally don't review dim sum places because they're pretty much all the same to me. However, I thought I should review Sunshine because I really enjoyed the experience. All other dim sum places in Chinatown are crawling with tourists, way over-priced, and don't even taste that good. Sunshine is not that crowded, the food is good, and it's cheap. Between the two of us, we ordered 7 little plates and our total came out to $24. This actually makes me not want to write a review because I want to be selfish and keep this place to myself. Would definitely come back next time I find myself in Chinatown looking for dim sum!

OMG! This place is awesome! I like that it's inside Chinatown and not yet overrun by tourists. The food is amazing! Whenever I go, the rice and broccoli is always a staple as well as the fluffy pork buns. Also, having random people besides my party be seated at the same table is awesome.

Really good dim sum.  Was really busy when we went there.  They ended up opening the basement.  Don't expect carts downstairs.  There's no shame in getting a tray and your stamp card and going upstairs to get the items you want.  But then again we were with family who know the staff.  Definitely adds to the experience!!

If you're like me, you tend to judge restaurants on two major factors: quality of food and price. In New York, there are very few restaurants that get a high score on the price front, good quality or no. Sunshine 27 is one of the only places I've ever been to that somehow manages to have sumptuous food that fills you up and doesn't drain your wallet. Thanks to that, it's now one of my favorite restaurants in New York and is a place my friends and I go to weekly to grab lunch. I can't recommend it enough.
